Q. Why even used inheritance ? Could have gone with directly specific type of duck.
1. Used inheritance because there could be same functionality among many ducks.
2. Also while using or expressing duck behaviour i won't have to create specific type of duck object.
    eg: List<Duck>
    otherwise :
        List<MallardDuck>
        List<RubberDuck>
        List<DecoyDuck>
        List<RedheadDuck>

Q. What problems faced with inheritance?
1. If we are adding any new functionality, there is possibility that that functionality would not be
   applicable for all child classes.
   For eg :
        All types of duck does not fly. Like RubberDuck, DecoyDuck
        All types of duck does not quack. Like DecoyDuck, RubberDuck

   So we will have to override that functionality across all child classes that does not support that functionality.
   eg : @Override
        public void fly() {} // in RedheadDuck and DecoyDuck

2. While runtime we cannot change the behaviour.
   Eg: If any duck got injured, that cannot swim.
   But since we have gone with inheritance, it does not allow use to change at runtime

